<DOC><DOCNO> AP900529-0213 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-90 2226EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a e BC-WKD--OnShow Adv00   05-29 0679</FIRST><SECOND>BC-WKD--On Show, Adv 00,0783</SECOND><NOTE>$adv00</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE><HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD><HEAD>On Show: Museum and Gallery Shows and Exhibits</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The Museum of Fine Arts in Houston has opened its gallery of FarEastern Art after a closing of more than two years because of spacelimitations.   The gallery, which opened on May 12, includes more than 60paintings, sculptures and ceramics from Japan, China and India.Recent acquisitions are a 6th century Japanese Haniwa Warrior ofterra-cotta, and a pair of Japanese six-panel screens illustratingthe ``Tale of Genji'' from the late 17th and early 18th century.   Elsewhere, the Luman Reed Gallery will open at the New YorkHistorical Society in New York City, presenting the 18th and 19thcentury art patron's entire collection of American and Europeanpaintings for the first time in more than 100 years.   The gallery will open on Nov. 13.   Here is a list of exhibits and shows at other galleries andmuseums in the United States:</TEXT><BYLINE>CHANDLER, Ariz.</BYLINE><TEXT>      Chandler Center for the Arts:   ``Patrick Nagel: The Art of Technology,'' a speciallycommissioned body of work by Intel Corp. that uses subjectsinspired by technology and leisure. June 1-July 4.</TEXT><BYLINE>CHICAGO</BYLINE><TEXT>      Deson Saunders Art Gallery:   Works by eight Pittsburgh artists. Through July 10.</TEXT><BYLINE>FORT WORTH, Texas</BYLINE><TEXT>      Amon Carter Museum:   ``Of Time and Place: Walker Evans and Williams Christenberry.''Through June 24.</TEXT><BYLINE>NEW YORK</BYLINE><TEXT>      Whitney Museum of American Art:   ``Ree Morton, Signs of Love.'' Through July 22.   Maurice Prendergast retrospective. Through Sept. 2.      Brooklyn Museum:   ``American Artists of the Alfred Stieglitz Circle.'' ThroughJune 18.      Museum of the City of New York:   ``The Passing Scene,'' the world of New York in the 1930s.Through Oct. 29.      Salander-O'Reilly Galleries:   Sculpture by Michael Steiner. Through May 31.   ``Marsden Hartley: The Late Figure Works.'' June 4-June 30.      Intar Gallery:   ``Danny Tisdale: The Black Museum.'' Through July 6.      Union Square Gallery:   ``Photo-Metallics andamp; Hand Colored Photographs,'' Carlos RenePerez. Through June 30.      Dyansen Gallery:   ``Original Paintings,'' Diana Kan. Through May 31.      Gallery Henoch:   Works by Robert Neffson. Through May 30.      Pace-MacGill Gallery:   ``Vintage Photographs,'' Rene Magritte. Through June 30.      International Center of Photography:   ``Marilyn Bridges: The Sacred and the Secular, A Decade ofAerial Photography.'' June 15-Sept. 2.   ``Eyes of the Time: Photojournalism in America.'' June 29-Aug. 19   ``Man Ray's Fashion Photography.'' Sept. 7-Nov. 25.      New York Historical Society:   ``Nicolino Calyo: Nineteenth-Century Views of New York.''Through June 10.   ``Below the Line: Living Poor in America.'' Through June 29.      Gallery International 57   ``Viennese Women.'' Through June 16.      Washburn Gallery:   ``In Review: Bolotowsky, Mason, Scarlett, Shaw.'' Through June29.      National Academy of Design:   ``Prize-Winning Drawings From the Roman Academy, 1682-1754.''Through Sept. 2.      American Museum of Natural History:   ``African Reflections: Art From Northeastern Zaire.'' Nationaltour starts January 1991.      Place des Antiquaires:   ``Chinnery and the China Coast.'' Through June 2.      Bronx Museum of the Arts:   ``A Decade of the Marketplace.'' June 12-Sept. 3.</TEXT><BYLINE>OXFORD, Ohio</BYLINE><TEXT>      Miami Unversity Art Museum:   ``Celebrating Cultural Diversity: Selections From theInternational Folk Art Collection.'' Through Aug. 10.</TEXT><BYLINE>PHOENIX</BYLINE><TEXT>      Phoenix Art Museum:   ``Graphic Design in America: A Visual Language History.''Through June 1